primarily to literature to illuminate the undeniable blind spots in white women's comprehension of their advantage. The contributors cover extensive historical ground, from early captivity narratives of white women in seventeenth-century America up to the present-day trials of Louise Woodward and Manjit Basuta, both British nannies accused of causing the deaths of their infant charges in the United States. Their wide-ranging discussions also include representations of white women in Native American, Latin American, African, Asian, and Middle Eastern contexts. The volume ultimately makes the case that, by creating alternative scenarios to particular ethical, political, or emotional problems against which readers and characters test their responses, literature forms an ideal vehicle for exploring white women's actual and potential roles in their efforts to undercut the oppressive force of whiteness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aEthics in literature. 0aRace in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezUnited States. 0aWomen, White, in literature. 0aWomen, White. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh1 aAmmons, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChvany, Peter A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonzett, Delia Caparoso, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoshy, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrebs, Paula M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Melissa Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNajmi, Samina